solution.p:
In theInverse Trigonometric Functions Section, we found two solutions to the equation \sin(\theta)=1/2,
\theta=\frac{\pi}{6} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta=\frac{5\pi}{6} 
These solutions are two common angles on the unit circle that have a sine value of 1/2.

        	Because sine is a periodic function, we can use these two initial solutions to solve for all other solutions. Recall that the period of sine is 2\pi. Therefore, to find another solution on the graph, we can add 2\pi to \pi/6
        	 \theta = \frac{\pi}{6} + 2\pi = \frac{\pi}{6} + \frac{12\pi}{6} = \frac{13\pi}{6}
			We could also subtract 2\pi from \pi/6 to give us yet another solution.
			 \theta = \frac{\pi}{6} - 2\pi = \frac{\pi}{6} - \frac{12\pi}{6} = -\frac{11\pi}{6} 
			These two additional solutions are shown on the graph below.

We can relate these solution sets back to the intersection points on the graph above. When k=0, we get our two initial solutions: 
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{6}+2\pi k = \frac{\pi}{6} + 2\pi\cdot 0 = \frac{\pi}{6} + 0 = \frac{\pi}{6}
and
 \theta = \frac{5\pi}{6}+2\pi k = \frac{5\pi}{6} + 2\pi\cdot 0 = \frac{5\pi}{6} + 0 = \frac{5\pi}{6}

When k=1, we get
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{6}+2\pi k = \frac{\pi}{6} + 2\pi\cdot 1 = \frac{\pi}{6} + 2\pi = \frac{\pi}{6} + \frac{12\pi}{6} = \frac{13\pi}{6}
and
 \theta = \frac{5\pi}{6}+2\pi k = \frac{5\pi}{6} + 2\pi\cdot 1 = \frac{5\pi}{6} + 2\pi = \frac{5\pi}{6} +\frac{12\pi}{6} = \frac{17\pi}{6}
This corresponds to the two solutions to the right of our initial solutions on the graph.

To solve this equation, we need to identify all angles, \theta, that have a tangent value of 1. We previously found two solutions to the equation \tan(\theta)=1,
\theta=\frac{\pi}{4} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta=\frac{5\pi}{4} 
These solutions are two common angles on the unit circle that have a tangent value of 1. However, if we look at the graph of f(\theta)=\tan(\theta) to see where it intersects with the horizontal line y=1, we can see that there are an infinite number of solutions to the equation \tan(\theta)=1.

Since there are no common angles on the unit circle for which \cos(\theta)=\frac{1}{4}, we must apply the inverse cosine function and solve for \theta approximately. Using our calculator, we get that
    
        \theta=\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\approx 1.318 \text{ radians}
    
    We can check this solution by evaluating \cos(1.318); since \cos(1.318)\approx0/2501\approx\frac{1}{4}, we can be confident that the angle we found satisfies \cos(\theta)=\frac{1}{4}.
